WEBVTT

00:09.140 --> 00:13.140
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:29.020 --> 00:34.420
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.980 --> 00:38.780
And here are your hosts.

00:43.900 --> 00:46.300
This is David Carson and David Cruz.

00:46.640 --> 00:49.960
Few characters in either science fiction or fantasy have been as fascinating to readers

00:49.960 --> 00:51.200
as Conan the Barbarian.

00:51.560 --> 00:56.500
Conan is the creation of Robert E. Howard, a writer of the 1930s who lived in cross-plains,

00:56.640 --> 00:56.880
Texas.

00:57.400 --> 01:02.140
Howard filled the pulp magazines of his day with westerns, detective stories, horror stories,

01:02.140 --> 01:04.920
science fantasy, just about anything that would sell.

01:05.360 --> 01:09.440
But he became best known for his tales of heroic fantasy, particularly the ones that

01:09.440 --> 01:10.140
involved Conan.

01:10.720 --> 01:15.640
Conan was a giant barbarian who lived a swashbuckling life in the mythical, hiberian age that Howard

01:15.640 --> 01:16.100
created.

01:16.740 --> 01:19.100
There is nothing fancy or subtle about Conan.

01:19.580 --> 01:22.380
He survives and flourishes by pure muscle and swordplay.

01:23.220 --> 01:26.700
Howard's writing was colorful and exciting, and perfectly matched his hero.

01:33.080 --> 01:35.800
Howard committed suicide in 1936 at the age of 30.

01:36.240 --> 01:39.140
He left a number of unfinished Conan manuscripts and story ideas.

01:39.760 --> 01:43.740
And the character of Conan was so appealing to readers that authors have recently been

01:43.740 --> 01:47.560
writing new material on him or finishing Howard's own incomplete stories.

01:48.360 --> 01:52.460
Noted science fiction and fantasy author L. Spray DeKamp has written Conan's stories

01:52.460 --> 01:55.780
and become interested enough in Howard's life to write a biography of him.

01:56.260 --> 01:58.980
We asked DeKamp if Howard was anything like Conan.

01:59.640 --> 02:03.740
Well, everybody knows that Conan is an idealization of Howard.

02:04.460 --> 02:09.140
In other words, the kind of person that Howard thought he would have liked to have been the

02:09.140 --> 02:13.860
ruthless, domineering, footloose, irresponsible adventurer.

02:15.580 --> 02:22.120
Actually, Robert, with no respect for laws and regulations.

02:23.640 --> 02:25.360
But the key word here is idealization.

02:25.800 --> 02:27.820
DeKamp says Howard and Conan were nothing alike.

02:28.840 --> 02:31.300
Actually Robert was just the opposite type.

02:32.160 --> 02:39.620
Except for hot tempers and chivalrous attitude toward women, they had nothing in common.

02:40.410 --> 02:57.840
Robert Howard was shy, bookish, compassionate, extremely polite, and socially timid.

02:58.900 --> 03:05.440
And he's so law abiding that he wouldn't cut across the neighbor's lot even,

03:05.540 --> 03:07.560
although everybody else in Cross Plains did.

03:08.960 --> 03:15.360
He was just about as different from the character Conan in the stories as a person could be.

03:16.280 --> 03:21.320
DeKamp believes Howard yearned to live in a past age, some more heroic time than the present.

03:22.560 --> 03:29.480
Well, Robert was always talking a lot about how he wished that he thought he'd been really in his element

03:29.480 --> 03:37.320
if he'd been born on the Texan frontier in the 19th century or in some barbarian society

03:37.320 --> 03:40.160
like the ancient Gauls or Gauls or somebody.

03:41.180 --> 03:50.780
Well, I think he'd have had a very unpleasant surprise because it wasn't his temperament at all.

03:51.360 --> 03:54.240
He was shy, bookish, introvert.

03:55.700 --> 03:58.880
Finally DeKamp reveals that Howard had a serious mental problem.

03:59.940 --> 04:06.320
He had an outsized monkey on his back and he was doomed from some way back.

04:06.860 --> 04:09.860
He planned his suicide ever since he was a little boy.

04:10.400 --> 04:15.320
He told his mother when he was a little kitty that when mama, when you die, I want to die with you.

04:15.940 --> 04:20.700
And the foolish woman, I think, probably sort of giggled and encouraged him.

04:21.180 --> 04:26.660
It was long plans and several people knew about it, but they didn't do anything.

04:27.300 --> 04:31.460
The only thing you could have done with Robert was if you'd gotten him to a good shrink early enough,

04:32.540 --> 04:35.740
quite a good many years before he actually killed himself,

04:36.080 --> 04:40.120
something might have been done, but that of course is uncertain.

04:41.280 --> 04:46.660
Howard wrote some 21 Conan stories, most of which appeared in Weird Tales in the 1930s.

04:47.080 --> 04:51.940
Only one novel, Conan the Conqueror, was published and that was some time after Howard's death.

04:52.480 --> 04:54.180
More next time about Robert E. Howard.

