12:25.360 --> 12:28.220
Robert E. Howard, the creator of Conan the Barbarian, was a paradox.

12:28.840 --> 12:35.420
He was brought up on the arid plains of west central Texas, lived in the small country town of cross plains, and hardly did any traveling.

12:35.800 --> 12:38.220
And he died by his own hand at the age of 30.

12:38.220 --> 12:42.760
Yet Howard wrote heroic stories that were set in the mythical age after the fall of Atlantis.

12:43.300 --> 12:47.120
He was fascinated with the misty, cold northern landscape in which he set his tales.

12:47.880 --> 12:54.880
Conan, his greatest creation, was a barbarian from the north, a giant who strode across the Hyborian age, wielding a bloody broadsword.

12:55.200 --> 12:56.720
But Howard's life was a quiet one.

12:57.220 --> 12:59.280
He was introverted, bookish, and shy.

12:59.820 --> 13:02.520
As far as we know, he was never in a brawl or fight of any kind.

13:03.060 --> 13:06.760
Why did Howard create Conan and place him in a mythical northern landscape?

13:06.760 --> 13:11.920
What sort of mind would conceive of a barbarian hero, a loner who spurned civilization?

13:12.600 --> 13:19.320
We spoke with Dr. Charlotte Laughlin, a professor at Howard Payne University in Brownwood, Texas, not far from Howard's home in cross plains.

13:19.800 --> 13:23.780
Dr. Laughlin is intimate with Howard's life and has done research for a Howard biography.

13:24.360 --> 13:27.340
She believes there are some reasons for Howard's obsession with Conan.

13:28.500 --> 13:33.520
I think that again, it was a sort of explanation for why he did not fit in with other people.

13:33.520 --> 13:36.460
He liked to believe I am the last barbarian.

13:36.920 --> 13:46.860
It's because in my type, Will Preveal, he liked to believe that the other people had a veneer of civilization on them that got them away from the basics that were really important.

13:47.240 --> 13:57.400
And if you've read his correspondence with Lovecraft, they had long arguments about the physical versus the intellectual needs of a society.

13:57.400 --> 14:11.100
And Howard would say that in the tough country where he lived, you had to be physically fit and he spent a great deal of his life, his adult life, trying to be physically fit, boxing and working out and that sort of thing.

14:17.620 --> 14:24.380
Howard also was fascinated with the legendary past of Britain, especially with the savage Picks and the early heroes of Celtic myth.

14:24.380 --> 14:29.340
Some of his Conan stories, such as Across the Dark River, have ancient Britain as their setting.

14:30.220 --> 14:33.300
We asked Dr. Laughlin why Howard was so drawn to this material.

14:34.280 --> 14:40.180
He claimed that he was full blood Irish and they were the Irish kings like some other people we know claim to be.

14:40.840 --> 14:45.180
But there's no evidence that he certainly was not full blood Irish. People have traced his genealogy.

14:45.380 --> 14:52.280
But this was part of his image of himself. He was trying to project other people and trying to create for himself.

14:53.480 --> 15:02.800
There again he wrote at one time that he wrote about the barren, cold, windswept, damp areas, even though he lived here.

15:03.080 --> 15:08.900
I think that again might be a sort of wish fulfillment who wouldn't like to be someplace where it's cold on a day like this.

15:09.120 --> 15:18.760
He wanted to be away from where he was because I don't think we can underestimate the anger and frustration that was boiling around in Robert Howard all the time.

15:18.760 --> 15:25.780
I see it in all of his poetry and a great deal of his fiction.

15:26.800 --> 15:33.760
Cross Plains neighbors say that he had a big tree stump out by his yard and I believe it was a sledgehammer, not an axe.

15:34.200 --> 15:39.980
And sometimes in the middle of the day he would go out there and you could just see that he was so tense and he would take that sledgehammer

15:39.980 --> 15:43.360
and he would just wham it and wham it and wham it on this tree stump.

15:43.360 --> 15:54.120
That a tremendous amount of anger he didn't fit in with other people. He wanted to be somewhere else so he wrote about something that was like nothing he had experienced.

16:01.060 --> 16:05.900
Howard wrote Reims of Fantasy in the pulp era of the 1930s, most of it for weird tales.

16:05.900 --> 16:13.280
We asked Dr. Loughlin why Howard wrote Fantasy. Did he have the talent to write more realistic fiction that might have gotten him out of the pulp ghetto?

16:14.420 --> 16:22.620
He may have had the talent but I certainly don't believe he was capable of writing realistic fiction. He was not that closely tied to reality himself.

16:23.040 --> 16:27.940
I don't believe he ever could have written realistic novels. He had to write fantasies of some sort.

