18:14.300 --> 18:20.700
Fantasy writer Robert E. Howard grew up in the 1920s and the 1930s in the small Texas town of Cross Plains.

18:21.100 --> 18:24.600
But he wasn't like other small town boys. He kept to himself quite a bit.

18:24.600 --> 18:32.240
He read a lot and used a vivid imagination to create his memorable heroic fantasies, for most of which are the stories of Conan the Barbarian.

18:32.920 --> 18:37.500
Howard died in 1936, but some of the people in Cross Plains still remember him clearly.

18:38.080 --> 18:44.860
We spoke with two of Howard's friends, Jack Scott, the editor of the Cross Plains newspaper, and Leroy Butler, Howard's next door neighbor.

18:45.380 --> 18:51.100
Butler remembers a time when he and Howard were still children and they bought some swords from a mail order company in New York.

18:52.120 --> 18:58.960
But we ordered those things and we'd get out in the backyard and wrap a band down a hamster around our hedge-like pirate.

19:00.260 --> 19:03.480
And we'd get out fence with those things.

19:04.260 --> 19:09.960
Of course we didn't dare, you know, hit each other with them because they were, they'd have gone through you.

19:11.840 --> 19:19.900
But we did that quite a bit. We had an immense live oak tree in our backyard and we'd get out there and shade that oak tree in.

19:22.780 --> 19:33.360
Pretend that we were back maybe in the dark ages or something or in the time of the Spanish man.

19:34.880 --> 19:40.800
Things like that. He had things like that on his mind all the time.

19:41.140 --> 19:44.400
Butler says that Robert was a loner dedicated to his writing.

19:45.420 --> 19:48.560
Robert never married. He never seemed interested in girls.

19:51.740 --> 19:58.560
And he did have one girlfriend there in Cross Plains for a time. I'd see him out in the car driving around once in a while.

19:59.420 --> 20:01.620
But I don't think that lasted long.

20:02.420 --> 20:07.400
He was just wrapped up in his, in his work writing those stories.

20:09.480 --> 20:15.860
And he had a blast-in-back porch on the southeast side of the house there.

20:17.520 --> 20:20.620
And it wasn't too far from my mother's bedroom.

20:22.460 --> 20:28.500
And a lot of times at night he'd wake her up with that typewriter clock in, you know, at 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning.

20:28.500 --> 20:36.480
Some inspiration. He'd probably be laying there in bed and think of something and he'd get up and write it down right quick.

20:39.360 --> 20:41.280
And he just worked all hours.

20:43.100 --> 20:45.980
Jack Scott also comments on Howard's unusual personality.

20:46.780 --> 20:52.040
Howard was a little on the, a little, little on the odd side. He wasn't an animal.

20:52.040 --> 20:56.660
Howard was very many people. He was rather a loaf. But he was a big robust man.

20:57.440 --> 21:02.480
To me he was a combination of, uh, Edgar Allen and Poe and Jack London.

21:02.740 --> 21:04.660
If you can imagine that two together.

21:05.900 --> 21:11.180
In 1936, when Howard's mother was dying of a terminal illness, Howard took his own life.

21:12.180 --> 21:16.480
I remember, I remember the morning he, he, he killed himself very well.

21:17.360 --> 21:20.300
I heard on the street that Robert Howard had just shot himself.

21:20.720 --> 21:28.040
I immediately jumped in my car and ran down there and got down there and a few neighbors had gathered.

21:29.000 --> 21:38.540
It wasn't generally known over town, but the old justice of the peace was standing there on the gallery, the front porch.

21:38.540 --> 21:41.560
When I walked up he called me and said, come here Jack.

21:42.320 --> 21:51.660
I stepped up there and he took me into the bedroom and he pointed to an old underwood top rider who had the full lines written on it there.

21:52.800 --> 22:04.220
Howard had, when he had been told that his mother wouldn't live throughout the day, he went to this top rider, wrote these full lines,

22:04.220 --> 22:07.440
walked outside, sat down his car and shot his head off.

22:08.220 --> 22:11.520
And this old JP asked me what these full lines meant.

22:13.100 --> 22:20.040
They said, I'm sure you've read them all, fled all done, so let me on the tire. The feast is over, the lamps expire.

